                          <p>{% trans %}This site is mainly devoted to radar images from the ERS satellite, a satellite designed and launched by the European Space Agency in 1991. Images from the JERS radar satellite are also used in some applications.<br>Radar systems are active. They use centimetric electromagnetic waves (microwave range) to illuminate the earth's surface and measure the signals reflected by the surface (backscattering phenomenon). The assembly of the responses obtained taking into account the ground positions of the plots concerned allows the construction of images in a geometry close to the cartographic geometry.<br>Very important general property of radar images: they can be obtained day and night, regardless of cloudy conditions and precipitation; which makes it easier to create mosaics with many scenes, as shown in the illustration on this page. In a humid tropical context where cloud cover is almost permanent, 17 images were assembled in a few weeks.<br>The main characteristics of the system that influence the interaction of the wave with the earth's surface, and hence the properties of the image, are wavelength, polarization and spatial resolution. The spatial resolutions of ERS and JERS were similar, around 25m. These are the wavelengths and polarizations that explain the differences observed between images, VV polarization and wavelength of value 6 cm, classified in Band C, for ERS, and HH polarization, band L (wavelength 25cm) , for JERS. We will come back briefly later to the differences in sensitivity of the two bands C and L to roughness and vegetation cover. Polarization relates to the orientation of the electric field, in reception and in transmission. This double orientation of the field influences the backscattering of a given target and plays a role, along with the wavelength, on the nature of the images for a given landscape. You will find more information on ESA and ENSG courses available online:<br>https://sentinels.copernicus.eu/web/sentinel/missions/sentinel-1/sar-basic-theory-and-practical-exercises-with-snap-english<br>and cours-fad-public.ensg.eu/course/view.php?id=94<br>In the following, a short animation will recall the main properties of the images and several applications will be presented to show the interest of ERS images in different contexts (successively: relief, vegetation zone, coast, town of Kourou, Saut Maripa on the Oyapock river )<br>Complément Animation Video: <br>Principales caractéristiques du système radar, mode actif, jour et nuit, insensible aux nuages.<br> Main features of the radar system, active mode, day and night, insensitive to clouds and rain.{% endtrans %}</p>
						  
						  
						 
