                          <h2>{% trans %}Behavior of microwaves{% endtrans %}</h2>
                          <h3>{% trans %}Behavior of microwaves on different media{% endtrans %}</h3>
                          <p>{% trans %}Let us quickly summarize how the radar response evolves with the properties of the surface based on the previous examples. The waves do not penetrate the surface of the water. If the surface is smooth, the reflection is specular, with no return to the antenna, and the image is dark. If the surface is rougher the response increases and the image becomes brighter. Note that the roughness of the surface is evaluated relative to the wavelength, with a roughness threshold separating the smooth and rough media of the order of a quarter of the wavelength (see the application above. 'Maripa jump '). In built-up areas, walls and other structures generally lead to strong responses and these areas then appear as light or even white spots on the images. (see the example 'the city of Kourou'). On vegetation and other natural environments, the very diverse surface conditions generally lead to responses that allow them to be differentiated. The response of the vegetation depends on a large number of parameters related to the biomass and the structure of the plants. The penetration into the canopy increases with the wavelength, which leads to different contrasts between bands C (ERS) and L (JERS) (see the application on the coastal plain of Kourou below). When the forest cover is dense and homogeneous, the energy response of the canopy is more uniform but, for geometric reasons, the radar image then essentially reflects the forms of the relief (See the example 'relief').{% endtrans %}</p>

